# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heif-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heif-format/avif] An AVIF file is designed to be a conformant HEIF file for both image items and image sequences.
[src:heif-format/avif] Specifically, this specification follows the recommendations given in "Annex I: Guidelines On Defining New Image Formats and Brands" of HEIF.
[src:heif-format/avif] This specification reuses syntax and semantics used in the specification for the AV1 Codec ISO Media File Format Binding.
[src:heif-format/avif] In tests by Netflix in 2020, AVIF showed better compression efficiency than JPEG, as well as better detail preservation, fewer blocking artifacts and less color bleeding around hard edges in composites of natural images, text, and graphics.
[src:heif-format/avif] AVIF has been supported by all major web browsers since 2024, with over 93% of users worldwide on compatible browsers.
[src:heif-format/avif] On 14 December 2018, Netflix published the first .avif sample images.
[src:heif-format/avif] In November 2020, HDR sample images with PQ transfer function and BT.2020 color primaries were published.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] A **container format** (informally, sometimes called a **wrapper**) or **metafile** is a file format that allows multiple data streams to be embedded into a single file, usually along with metadata for identifying and further detailing those streams.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Notable examples of container formats include archive files (such as the ZIP format) and formats used for multimedia playback (such as Matroska, MP4, and AVI).
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Among the earliest cross-platform container formats were Distinguished Encoding Rules and the 1985 Interchange File Format.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Although containers may identify how data or metadata is encoded, they do not actually provide instructions about how to decode that data.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] A program that can open a container must also use an appropriate codec to decode its contents.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] If the program doesn't have the required algorithm, it can't use the contained data.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] In these cases, programs usually emit an error message that complains of a missing codec, which users may be able to acquire.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Container formats can be made to wrap any kind of data.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Though there are some examples of such file formats (e.g.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Microsoft Windows's DLL files), most container formats are specialized for specific data requirements.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] For example, since audio and video streams can be coded and decoded with many different algorithms, a container format may be used to provide the appearance of a single file format to users of multimedia playback software.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] This is the difference in file-size between two files with the same content in a different container.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Support for advanced codec functionality.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Older formats such as AVI do not support new codec features like B-frames, VBR audio or VFR video natively.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] The format may be "hacked" to add support, but this creates compatibility problems.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Support for advanced content, such as chapters, subtitles, meta-tags, user-data.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] In addition to pure container formats, which specify *only* the wrapper but not the coding, a number of file formats specify *both* a storage layer and the coding, as part of modular design and forward compatibility.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Examples include the JPEG File Interchange Format (JFIF), for containing JPEG data, and Portable Network Graphics (PNG) formats.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] The container file is used to identify and interleave different data types.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] In most cases, the file header, most of the metadata and the synchro chunks are specified by the container format.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] For example, container formats exist for optimized, low-quality, internet video streaming which differs from high-quality Blu-ray streaming requirements.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Container format parts have various names: "chunks" as in RIFF and PNG, "atoms" in QuickTime/MP4, "packets" in MPEG-TS (from the communications term), and "segments" in JPEG.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] The main content of a chunk is called the "data" or "payload".
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Most container formats have chunks in sequence, each with a header, while TIFF instead stores offsets.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Modular chunks make it easy to recover other chunks in case of file corruption or dropped frames or bit slip, while offsets result in framing errors in cases of bit slip.
[src:heif-format/digital-container-format] Other flexible containers can hold many types of audio and video, as well as other media.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF can store images encoded with multiple coding formats, for example both SDR and HDR images.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEVC is an image and video encoding format and the default image codec used with HEIF.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF files containing HEVC-encoded images are also known as **HEIC** files and are mandated to use the `.heic` filename extension or `.heics` as stated in the standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Such files require less storage space than the equivalent-quality JPEG files of the same images.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF files are a special case of the ISO base media file format (ISOBMFF, ISO/IEC 14496-12), first defined in 2001 as a shared part of MP4 and JPEG 2000.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Introduced in 2015, it was developed by the Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG) and is defined as Part 12 within the MPEG-H media suite (ISO/IEC 23008-12).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The requirements and main use cases of HEIF were defined in 2013.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The technical development of the specification took about one and a half years and was finalized in the middle of 2015.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Apple was the first major adopter of the format in 2017 with the introduction of iOS 11 using the HEIC variant.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] While HEIC became the default for iPhones, it is possible to revert the settings to allow photos to be recorded in the JPEG format.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Android devices containing the appropriate hardware encoders received support for HEIC files with the release of Android 10 (2019).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Although HEIC is gaining in popularity, it is not universally supported; Adobe Photoshop is an example of common image-editing software that only supports HEIC with color depth of 8-bit, and not 10- or 12-bit.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] As of 2022 camera hardware (including on mobile devices) is increasingly supporting HEIC file output, with color depth often higher than 8-bit color.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Storage of individual images, image properties and thumbnails.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] by the rendering software using editing instructions stored separately in the HEIF file.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] These instructions (rectangular cropping, rotation by one, two or three quarter-turns, timed graphic overlays, etc.) and images are stored separately in the HEIF file, and describe specific transformations to be applied to the input images.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The storage overhead of derived images is small.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] animation), their properties and thumbnails.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Different prediction options can be used in order to exploit the temporal and spatial similarities between the images.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Hence, file sizes can be drastically reduced when many images are stored in the same HEIF file.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] These data are not displayed as such, but used in various forms to complement another image item.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] and similar metadata which accompany the images stored in the HEIF file.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] As users cannot easily tell what encoding and encoding parameters an image was stored in, the HEIF container format can be confusing and makes comparison statements like “HEIF is better than JPEG” vague and inaccurate.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The Multi-Image Application Format (MIAF) is a restricted subset of HEIF specified as part of MPEG-A.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It defines a set of additional constraints to simplify format options, specific alpha plane formats, profiles and levels as well as metadata formats and brands, and rules for how to extend the format.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC, ITU-T H.265) is an encoding format for graphic data, first standardized in 2013.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It is the primarily used and implied default codec for HEIF as specified in the normative Annex B to ISO/IEC 23008-12 *HEVC Image File Format*.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] While not introduced formally in the standard, the initialism or acronym *HEIC* (High-Efficiency Image Codec) is used as a *brand* and in the MIME subtypes `image/heic` and `image/heic-sequence`.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] If the content conforms to certain HEVC profiles, more specific brands can be used: *HEIX* for Main 10 of HEVC, *HEIM* for (Multiview) Main profile, and *HEIS* for (Scalable) Main (10) profile of L-HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] A HEIC photo takes up about half the space of an equivalent-quality JPEG file.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The initial HEIF specification already defined the means of storing HEVC-encoded intra images (*i-frames*) and HEVC-encoded image sequences in which inter prediction is applied in a constrained manner.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEVC image players are required to support rectangular cropping and rotation by one, two, and three quarter-turns.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The primary use case for the mandatory support for rotation by 90 degrees is for images where the camera orientation is incorrectly detected or inferred.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The rotation requirement makes it possible to manually adjust the orientation of a still image or an image sequence without needing to re-encode it.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Cropping enables the image to be re-framed without re-encoding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The HEVC file format also includes the option to store pre-derived images.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Samples in image sequence tracks must be either intra-coded images or inter-picture predicted images with reference to only intra-coded images.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] These constraints of inter-picture prediction reduce the decoding latency for accessing any particular image within a HEVC image sequence track.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The *.heic* and *.heics* file name extensions are conventionally used for HEVC-coded HEIF files.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Apple products, for instance, will only produce files with these extensions, which indicate clearly that the data went through HEVC encoding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Advanced Video Coding (AVC, ITU-T H.264) is an older encoding format for video and images, first standardized in 2003.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It is also specified as a codec to be supported in HEIF in normative Annex 5 to ISO/IEC 23008-12.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The registered MIME types are `image/avci` for still images and `image/avcs` for sequences.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Apple products support playback of AVC-encoded *.avci* still image files and *.avcs* image sequence files but will only generate *.heic* files.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] AV1 is a video encoding format that is intended to be royalty-free, developed by the Alliance for Open Media (AOMedia).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] AV1 Image File Format (AVIF) is an image format based on this codec.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The registered MIME type is `image/avif` for both still images and image sequences, and *.avif* is the file name extension.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The original JPEG standard is the most commonly used and widely supported lossy image coding format.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] It was first released in 1992 by ITU-T and ISO/IEC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Although Annex H to ISO/IEC 23008-12 specifies JPEG (and indirectly Motion JPEG) as a possible format for HEIF coded image data, it is used in HEIF only for thumbnails and other secondary images.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Therefore, neither a dedicated MIME subtype nor a special file extension is available for storage of JPEG files in HEIF container files.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] In 2017, Apple announced that it would adopt HEIC as the default image format in its new operating systems, gradually replacing JPEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] The proprietary image format WXAM (or wxHEPC) developed by Tencent (used within, e.g., WeChat) is apparently based upon HEVC, as is SharpP, which was developed by their SNG (Social Network Group) division.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] However, their container format may not be HEIF-compatible.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] In March 2017, SharpP switched to AVS2 and was renamed TPG (*Tiny Portable Graphics*).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] As of November 2025, only Safari supports HEIC format natively.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Edge, Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Safari support AVIF.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] HEIF itself is a container that may not be subject to additional royalty fees for commercial ISOBMFF licensees.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] Nokia also grants its patents on a royalty-free basis for non-commercial purposes.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-image-file-format] When containing images and image sequences encoded in a particular format (e.g., HEVC or AVC) its use becomes subject to the licensing of patents on the coding format.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] While AVC uses the integer discrete cosine transform (DCT) with 4×4 and 8×8 block sizes, HEVC uses both integer DCT and discrete sine transform (DST) with varied block sizes between 4×4 and 32×32.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In most ways, HEVC is an extension of the concepts in H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Both work by comparing different parts of a frame of video to find areas that are redundant, both within a single frame and between consecutive frames.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] These redundant areas are then replaced with a short description instead of the original pixels.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Effective use of these improvements requires much more signal processing capability for compressing the video but has less impact on the amount of computation needed for decompression.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC was standardized by the Joint Collaborative Team on Video Coding (JCT-VC), a collaboration between the ISO/IEC MPEG and ITU-T Study Group 16 VCEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The ISO/IEC group refers to it as MPEG-H Part 2 and the ITU-T as H.265.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The first version of the HEVC standard was ratified in January 2013 and published in June 2013.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The second version, with multiview extensions (MV-HEVC), range extensions (RExt), and scalability extensions (SHVC), was completed and approved in 2014 and published in early 2015.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Extensions for 3D video (3D-HEVC) were completed in early 2015, and extensions for screen content coding (SCC) were completed in early 2016 and published in early 2017, covering video containing rendered graphics, text, or animation as well as (or instead of) camera-captured video scenes.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In October 2017, the standard was recognized by a Primetime Emmy Engineering Award as having had a material effect on the technology of television.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC contains technologies covered by patents owned by the organizations that participated in the JCT-VC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Implementing a device or software application that uses HEVC may require a license from HEVC patent holders.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The ISO/IEC and ITU require companies that belong to their organizations to offer their patents on reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing (RAND) terms.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Patent licenses can be obtained directly from each patent holder, or through patent licensing bodies, such as MPEG LA, Access Advance, and Velos Media.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The combined licensing fees currently offered by all of the patent licensing bodies are higher than for AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The HEVC format was jointly developed by more than a dozen organisations across the world.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The majority of active patent contributions towards the development of the HEVC format came from five organizations: Samsung Electronics (4,249 patents), General Electric (1,127 patents), M&K Holdings (907 patents), NTT (878 patents), and JVC Kenwood (628 patents).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Other patent holders include Fujitsu, Apple, Canon, Columbia University, KAIST, Kwangwoon University, MIT, Sungkyunkwan University, Funai, Hikvision, KBS, KT, and NEC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In 2004, the ITU-T Video Coding Experts Group (VCEG) began a major study of technology advances that could enable the creation of a new video compression standard (or substantial compression-oriented enhancements of the H.264/MPEG-4 AVC standard).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In October 2004, various techniques for potential enhancement of the H.264/MPEG-4 AVC standard were surveyed.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In January 2005, at the next meeting of VCEG, VCEG began designating certain topics as "Key Technical Areas" (KTA) for further investigation.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] A software codebase called the KTA codebase was established for evaluating such proposals.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The KTA software was based on the Joint Model (JM) reference software that was developed by the MPEG & VCEG Joint Video Team for H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Additional proposed technologies were integrated into the KTA software and tested in experiment evaluations over the next four years.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Two approaches for standardizing enhanced compression technology were considered: either creating a new standard or creating extensions of H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The project had tentative names *H.265* and *H.NGVC* (Next-generation Video Coding), and was a major part of the work of VCEG until it evolved into the HEVC joint project with MPEG in 2010.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The preliminary requirements for NGVC were the capability to have a bit rate reduction of 50% at the same subjective image quality compared with the H.264/MPEG-4 AVC High profile, and computational complexity ranging from 1/2 to 3 times that of the High profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] NGVC would be able to provide 25% bit rate reduction along with 50% reduction in complexity at the same perceived video quality as the High profile, or to provide greater bit rate reduction with somewhat higher complexity.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The ISO/IEC Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG) started a similar project in 2007, tentatively named *High-performance Video Coding*.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] An agreement of getting a bit rate reduction of 50% had been decided as the goal of the project by July 2007.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Early evaluations were performed with modifications of the KTA reference software encoder developed by VCEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] By July 2009, experimental results showed average bit reduction of around 20% compared with AVC High Profile; these results prompted MPEG to initiate its standardization effort in collaboration with VCEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] MPEG and VCEG established a Joint Collaborative Team on Video Coding (**JCT-VC**) to develop the HEVC standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] A formal joint Call for Proposals on video compression technology was issued in January 2010 by VCEG and MPEG, and proposals were evaluated at the first meeting of the MPEG & VCEG Joint Collaborative Team on Video Coding (JCT-VC), which took place in April 2010.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] A total of 27 full proposals were submitted.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] At that meeting, the name *High Efficiency Video Coding* (HEVC) was adopted for the joint project.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Starting at that meeting, the JCT-VC integrated features of some of the best proposals into a single software codebase and a "Test Model under Consideration", and performed further experiments to evaluate various proposed features.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The first working draft specification of HEVC was produced at the third JCT-VC meeting in October 2010.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Many changes in the coding tools and configuration of HEVC were made in later JCT-VC meetings.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On January 25, 2013, the ITU announced that HEVC had received first stage approval (consent) in the ITU-T Alternative Approval Process (AAP).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On the same day, MPEG announced that HEVC had been promoted to Final Draft International Standard (FDIS) status in the MPEG standardization process.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On April 13, 2013, HEVC/H.265 was approved as an ITU-T standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The standard was formally published by the ITU-T on June 7, 2013, and by the ISO/IEC on November 25, 2013.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On July 11, 2014, MPEG announced that the 2nd edition of HEVC will contain three recently completed extensions which are the multiview extensions (MV-HEVC), the range extensions (RExt), and the scalability extensions (SHVC).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On October 29, 2014, HEVC/H.265 version 2 was approved as an ITU-T standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] It was then formally published on January 12, 2015.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On April 29, 2015, HEVC/H.265 version 3 was approved as an ITU-T standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On June 3, 2016, HEVC/H.265 version 4 was consented in the ITU-T and was not approved during a vote in October 2016.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On December 22, 2016, HEVC/H.265 version 4 was approved as an ITU-T standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 29, 2014, MPEG LA announced their HEVC license which covers the essential patents from 23 companies.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The first 100,000 "devices" (which includes software implementations) are royalty-free, and after that the fee is $0.20 per device up to an annual cap of $25 million.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This is significantly more expensive than the fees on AVC, which were $0.10 per device, with the same 100,000 waiver, and an annual cap of $6.5 million.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] MPEG LA does not charge any fee on the content itself, something they had attempted when initially licensing AVC, but subsequently dropped when content producers refused to pay it.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The license has been expanded to include the profiles in version 2 of the HEVC standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] When the MPEG LA terms were announced, commenters noted that a number of prominent patent holders were not part of the group.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Among these were AT&T, Microsoft, Nokia, and Motorola.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Speculation at the time was that these companies would form their own licensing pool to compete with or add to the MPEG LA pool.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Such a group was formally announced on March 26, 2015, as HEVC Advance.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The terms, covering 500 essential patents, were announced on July 22, 2015, with rates that depend on the country of sale, type of device, HEVC profile, HEVC extensions, and HEVC optional features.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Unlike the MPEG LA terms, HEVC Advance reintroduced license fees on content encoded with HEVC, through a revenue sharing fee.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The initial HEVC Advance license had a maximum royalty rate of US$2.60 per device for Region 1 countries and a content royalty rate of 0.5% of the revenue generated from HEVC video services.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Region 1 countries in the HEVC Advance license include the United States, Canada, European Union, Japan, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand, and others.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Region 2 countries are countries not listed in the Region 1 country list.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The HEVC Advance license had a maximum royalty rate of US$1.30 per device for Region 2 countries.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Unlike MPEG LA, there was no annual cap.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On top of this, HEVC Advance also charged a royalty rate of 0.5% of the revenue generated from video services encoding content in HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] When they were announced, there was considerable backlash from industry observers about the "unreasonable and greedy" fees on devices, which were about seven times that of the MPEG LA's fees.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Added together, a device would require licenses costing $2.80, twenty-eight times as expensive as AVC, as well as license fees on the content.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This led to calls for "content owners [to] band together and agree not to license from HEVC Advance".
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Others argued the rates might cause companies to switch to competing standards such as Daala and VP9.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On December 18, 2015, HEVC Advance announced changes in the royalty rates.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The changes include a reduction in the maximum royalty rate for Region 1 countries to US$2.03 per device, the creation of annual royalty caps, and a waiving of royalties on content that is free to end users.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The annual royalty caps for a company is US$40 million for devices, US$5 million for content, and US$2 million for optional features.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On February 3, 2016, Technicolor SA announced that they had withdrawn from the HEVC Advance patent pool and would be directly licensing their HEVC patents.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC Advance previously listed 12 patents from Technicolor.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Technicolor announced that they had rejoined on October 22, 2019.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On November 22, 2016, HEVC Advance announced a major initiative, revising their policy to allow software implementations of HEVC to be distributed directly to consumer mobile devices and personal computers royalty free, without requiring a patent license.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On March 31, 2017, Velos Media announced their HEVC license which covers the essential patents from Ericsson, Panasonic, Qualcomm Incorporated, Sharp, and Sony.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] As of April 2019, the MPEG LA HEVC patent list is 164 pages long.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Versions of the HEVC/H.265 standard using the ITU-T approval dates.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On February 29, 2012, at the 2012 Mobile World Congress, Qualcomm demonstrated a HEVC decoder running on an Android tablet, with a Qualcomm Snapdragon S4 dual-core processor running at 1.5 GHz, showing H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC versions of the same video content playing side by side.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In this demonstration, HEVC reportedly showed almost a 50% bit rate reduction compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On February 11, 2013, researchers from MIT demonstrated the world's first published HEVC ASIC decoder at the International Solid-State Circuits Conference (ISSCC) 2013.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Their chip was capable of decoding a 3840×2160p at 30 fps video stream in real time, consuming under 0.1 W of power.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On April 3, 2013, Ateme announced the availability of the first open source implementation of a HEVC software player based on the OpenHEVC decoder and GPAC video player which are both licensed under LGPL.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The OpenHEVC decoder supports the Main profile of HEVC and can decode 1080p at 30 fps video using a single core CPU.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] A live transcoder that supports HEVC and used in combination with the GPAC video player was shown at the ATEME booth at the NAB Show in April 2013.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On July 23, 2013, MulticoreWare announced, and made the source code available for the x265 HEVC Encoder Library under the GPL v2 license.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On August 8, 2013, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone announced the release of their HEVC-1000 SDK software encoder which supports the Main 10 profile, resolutions up to 7680×4320, and frame rates up to 120 fps.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On November 14, 2013, DivX developers released information on HEVC decoding performance using an Intel i7 CPU at 3.5 GHz with 4 cores and 8 threads.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On December 18, 2013, ViXS Systems announced shipments of their XCode (not to be confused with Apple's Xcode IDE for MacOS) 6400 SoC which was the first SoC to support the Main 10 profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On April 5, 2014, at the NAB show, eBrisk Video, Inc. and Altera Corporation demonstrated an FPGA-accelerated HEVC Main10 encoder that encoded 4Kp60/10-bit video in real-time, using a dual-Xeon E5-2697-v2 platform.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On August 13, 2014, Ittiam Systems announced availability of its third generation H.265/HEVC codec with 4:2:2 12-bit support.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 5, 2014, the Blu-ray Disc Association announced that the 4K Blu-ray Disc specification would support HEVC-encoded 4K video at 60 fps, the Rec.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] 2020 color space, high dynamic range (PQ and HLG), and 10-bit color depth.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] 4K Blu-ray Discs have a data rate of at least 50 Mbit/s and disc capacity up to 100 GB.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] 4K Blu-ray Discs and players became available for purchase in 2015 or 2016.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 9, 2014, Apple announced the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus which support HEVC/H.265 for FaceTime over cellular.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 18, 2014, Nvidia released the GeForce GTX 980 (GM204) and GTX 970 (GM204), which includes Nvidia NVENC, the world's first HEVC hardware encoder in a discrete graphics card.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On October 31, 2014, Microsoft confirmed that Windows 10 will support HEVC out of the box, according to a statement from Gabriel Aul, the leader of Microsoft Operating Systems Group's Data and Fundamentals Team.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Windows 10 Technical Preview Build 9860 added platform level support for HEVC and Matroska.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On November 3, 2014, Android Lollipop was released with out of the box support for HEVC using Ittiam Systems' software.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On January 5, 2015, ViXS Systems announced the XCode 6800 which is the first SoC to support the Main 12 profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On January 5, 2015, Nvidia officially announced the Tegra X1 SoC with full fixed-function HEVC hardware decoding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On January 22, 2015, Nvidia released the GeForce GTX 960 (GM206), which includes the world's first full fixed function HEVC Main/Main10 hardware decoder in a discrete graphics card.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On February 23, 2015, Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) announced that their UVD ASIC to be found in the Carrizo APUs would be the first x86 based CPUs to have a HEVC hardware decoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On February 27, 2015, VLC media player version 2.2.0 was released with robust support of HEVC playback.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The corresponding versions on Android and iOS are also able to play HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On March 31, 2015, VITEC announced the MGW Ace which was the first 100% hardware-based portable HEVC encoder that provides mobile HEVC encoding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On August 5, 2015, Intel launched Skylake products with full fixed function Main/8-bit decoding/encoding and hybrid/partial Main10/10-bit decoding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 9, 2015 Apple announced the Apple A9 chip, first used in the iPhone 6S, its first processor with a hardware HEVC decoder supporting Main 8 and 10.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This feature would not be unlocked until the release of iOS 11 in 2017.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On April 11, 2016, full HEVC (H.265) support was announced in the newest MythTV version (0.28).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On August 30, 2016, Intel officially announced 7th generation Core CPUs (Kaby Lake) products with full fixed function HEVC Main10 hardware decoding support.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 7, 2016 Apple announced the Apple A10 chip, first used in the iPhone 7, which included a hardware HEVC encoder supporting Main 8 and 10.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On October 25, 2016, Nvidia released the GeForce GTX 1050 Ti (GP107) and GeForce GTX 1050 (GP107), which includes full fixed function HEVC Main10/Main12 hardware encoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On June 5, 2017, Apple announced HEVC H.265 support in macOS High Sierra, iOS 11, tvOS, HTTP Live Streaming and Safari.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On June 25, 2017, Microsoft released a free HEVC app extension for Windows 10, enabling some Windows 10 devices with HEVC decoding hardware to play video using the HEVC format inside any app.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 19, 2017, Apple released iOS 11 and tvOS 11 with HEVC encoding & decoding support.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 25, 2017, Apple released macOS High Sierra with HEVC encoding & decoding support.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 28, 2017, GoPro released the Hero6 Black action camera, with 4K60P HEVC video encoding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On October 17, 2017, Microsoft removed HEVC decoding support from Windows 10 with the Version 1709 Fall Creators Update, making HEVC available instead as a separate, paid download from the Microsoft Store.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On November 2, 2017, Nvidia released the GeForce GTX 1070 Ti (GP104), which includes full fixed function HEVC Main10/Main12 hardware decoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On September 20, 2018, Nvidia released the GeForce RTX 2080 (TU104), which includes full fixed function HEVC Main 4:4:4 12 hardware decoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] On October 25, 2022, Chrome released version 107, which supports HEVC hardware decoding for all platforms "out of the box", if the hardware is supported.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In November 2025, an estimated 92.29% of browsers in use on desktop and mobile systems were able to play HEVC videos in HTML5 webpages, based on data from Can I Use.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Most video coding standards are designed primarily to achieve the highest coding efficiency.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Coding efficiency is the ability to encode video at the lowest possible bit rate while maintaining a certain level of video quality.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] There are two standard ways to measure the coding efficiency of a video coding standard, which are to use an objective metric, such as peak signal-to-noise ratio (PSNR), or to use subjective assessment of video quality.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Subjective assessment of video quality is considered to be the most important way to measure a video coding standard since humans perceive video quality subjectively.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC benefits from the use of larger coding tree unit (CTU) sizes.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This has been shown in PSNR tests with a HM-8.0 HEVC encoder where it was forced to use progressively smaller CTU sizes.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] For all test sequences, when compared with a 64×64 CTU size, it was shown that the HEVC bit rate increased by 2.2% when forced to use a 32×32 CTU size, and increased by 11.0% when forced to use a 16×16 CTU size.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In the Class A test sequences, where the resolution of the video was 2560×1600, when compared with a 64×64 CTU size, it was shown that the HEVC bit rate increased by 5.7% when forced to use a 32×32 CTU size, and increased by 28.2% when forced to use a 16×16 CTU size.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The tests showed that large CTU sizes increase coding efficiency while also reducing decoding time.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The HEVC Main Profile (MP) has been compared in coding efficiency to H.264/MPEG-4 AVC High Profile (HP), MPEG-4 Advanced Simple Profile (ASP), H.263 High Latency Profile (HLP), and H.262/MPEG-2 Main Profile (MP).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The video encoding was done for entertainment applications and twelve different bitrates were made for the nine video test sequences with a HM-8.0 HEVC encoder being used.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Of the nine video test sequences, five were at HD resolution, while four were at WVGA (800×480) resolution.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The bit rate reductions for HEVC were determined based on PSNR with HEVC having a bit rate reduction of 35.4% compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC HP, 63.7% compared with MPEG-4 ASP, 65.1% compared with H.263 HLP, and 70.8% compared with H.262/MPEG-2 MP.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC MP has also been compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC HP for subjective video quality.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The video encoding was done for entertainment applications and four different bitrates were made for nine video test sequences with a HM-5.0 HEVC encoder being used.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The subjective assessment was done at an earlier date than the PSNR comparison and so it used an earlier version of the HEVC encoder that had slightly lower performance.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The bit rate reductions were determined based on subjective assessment using mean opinion score values.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The overall subjective bitrate reduction for HEVC MP compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC HP was 49.3%.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) did a study to evaluate the subjective video quality of HEVC at resolutions higher than HDTV.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The five second video sequences showed people on a street, traffic, and a scene from the open source computer animated movie *Sintel*.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The video sequences were encoded at five different bitrates using the HM-6.1.1 HEVC encoder and the JM-18.3 H.264/MPEG-4 AVC encoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The subjective bit rate reductions were determined based on subjective assessment using mean opinion score values.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The study compared HEVC MP with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC HP and showed that, for HEVC MP, the average bitrate reduction based on PSNR was 44.4%, while the average bitrate reduction based on subjective video quality was 66.5%.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In a HEVC performance comparison released in April 2013, the HEVC MP and Main 10 Profile (M10P) were compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC HP and High 10 Profile (H10P) using 3840×2160 video sequences.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The video sequences were encoded using the HM-10.0 HEVC encoder and the JM-18.4 H.264/MPEG-4 AVC encoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The average bit rate reduction based on PSNR was 45% for inter frame video.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In a video encoder comparison released in December 2013, the HM-10.0 HEVC encoder was compared with the x264 encoder (version r2334) and the VP9 encoder (version v1.2.0-3088-ga81bd12).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The comparison used the Bjøntegaard-Delta bit-rate (BD-BR) measurement method, in which negative values tell how much lower the bit rate is reduced, and positive values tell how much the bit rate is increased for the same PSNR.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In the comparison, the HM-10.0 HEVC encoder had the highest coding efficiency and, on average, to get the same objective quality, the x264 encoder needed to increase the bit rate by 66.4%, while the VP9 encoder needed to increase the bit rate by 79.4%.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In a subjective video performance comparison released in May 2014, the JCT-VC compared the HEVC Main profile to the H.264/MPEG-4 AVC High profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The comparison used mean opinion score values and was conducted by the BBC and the University of the West of Scotland.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The video sequences were encoded using the HM-12.1 HEVC encoder and the JM-18.5 H.264/MPEG-4 AVC encoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The comparison used a range of resolutions and the average bit rate reduction for HEVC was 59%.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The average bit rate reduction for HEVC was 52% for 480p, 56% for 720p, 62% for 1080p, and 64% for 4K UHD.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In a subjective video codec comparison released in August 2014 by the EPFL, the HM-15.0 HEVC encoder was compared with the VP9 1.2.0–5183 encoder and the JM-18.8 H.264/MPEG-4 AVC encoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Four 4K resolutions sequences were encoded at five different bit rates with the encoders set to use an intra period of one second.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In the comparison, the HM-15.0 HEVC encoder had the highest coding efficiency and, on average, for the same subjective quality the bit rate could be reduced by 49.4% compared with the VP9 1.2.0–5183 encoder, and it could be reduced by 52.6% compared with the JM-18.8 H.264/MPEG-4 AVC encoder.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In August, 2016, Netflix published the results of a large-scale study comparing the leading open-source HEVC encoder, x265, with the leading open-source AVC encoder, x264 and the reference VP9 encoder, libvpx.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Using their advanced Video Multimethod Assessment Fusion (VMAF) video quality measurement tool, Netflix found that x265 delivered identical quality at bit rates ranging from 35.4% to 53.3% lower than x264, and from 17.8% to 21.8% lower than VP9.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC was designed to substantially improve coding efficiency compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC HP, i.e. to reduce bitrate requirements by half with comparable image quality, at the expense of increased computational complexity.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC was designed with the goal of allowing video content to have a data compression ratio of up to 1000:1.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Depending on the application requirements, HEVC encoders can trade off computational complexity, compression rate, robustness to errors, and encoding delay time.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Two of the key features where HEVC was improved compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC was support for higher resolution video and improved parallel processing methods.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC is targeted at next-generation HDTV displays and content capture systems which feature progressive scanned frame rates and display resolutions from QVGA (320×240) to 4320p (7680×4320), as well as improved picture quality in terms of noise level, color spaces, and dynamic range.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The HEVC video coding layer uses the same "hybrid" approach used in all modern video standards, starting from H.261, in that it uses inter-/intra-picture prediction and 2D transform coding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] A HEVC encoder first proceeds by splitting a picture into block shaped regions for the first picture, or the first picture of a random access point, which uses intra-picture prediction.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Intra-picture prediction is when the prediction of the blocks in the picture is based only on the information in that picture.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] For all other pictures, inter-picture prediction is used, in which prediction information is used from other pictures.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] After the prediction methods are finished and the picture goes through the loop filters, the final picture representation is stored in the decoded picture buffer.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Pictures stored in the decoded picture buffer can be used for the prediction of other pictures.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC was designed with the idea that progressive scan video would be used and no coding tools were added specifically for interlaced video.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Interlace specific coding tools, such as MBAFF and PAFF, are not supported in HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC instead sends metadata that tells how the interlaced video was sent.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Interlaced video may be sent either by coding each frame as a separate picture or by coding each field as a separate picture.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] For interlaced video HEVC can change between frame coding and field coding using Sequence Adaptive Frame Field (SAFF), which allows the coding mode to be changed for each video sequence.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This allows interlaced video to be sent with HEVC without needing special interlaced decoding processes to be added to HEVC decoders.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The HEVC standard supports color spaces such as generic film (colour filters using Illuminant C), NTSC, PAL, Rec.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] 2100, SMPTE 240M, sRGB, sYCC, xvYCC, XYZ, and externally specified color spaces such as Dolby Vision or HDR Vivid.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC supports color encoding representations such as RGB, YCbCr and ICtCp, and YCoCg.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC replaces 16×16 pixel macroblocks, which were used with previous standards, with coding tree units (CTUs) which can use larger block structures of up to 64×64 samples and can better sub-partition the picture into variable sized structures.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC initially divides the picture into CTUs which can be 64×64, 32×32, or 16×16 with a larger pixel block size usually increasing the coding efficiency.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC specifies four transform units (TUs) sizes of 4×4, 8×8, 16×16, and 32×32 to code the prediction residual.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] A CTB may be recursively partitioned into 4 or more TUs.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] TUs use integer basis functions based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In addition, 4×4 luma transform blocks that belong to an intra coded region are transformed using an integer transform that is derived from discrete sine transform (DST).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This provides a 1% bit rate reduction but was restricted to 4×4 luma transform blocks due to marginal benefits for the other transform cases.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Chroma uses the same TU sizes as luma so there is no 2×2 transform for chroma.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC uses a context-adaptive binary arithmetic coding (CABAC) algorithm that is fundamentally similar to CABAC in H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] CABAC is the only entropy encoder method that is allowed in HEVC while there are two entropy encoder methods allowed by H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] CABAC and the entropy coding of transform coefficients in HEVC were designed for a higher throughput than H.264/MPEG-4 AVC, while maintaining higher compression efficiency for larger transform block sizes relative to simple extensions.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] For instance, the number of context coded bins have been reduced by 8× and the CABAC bypass-mode has been improved in terms of its design to increase throughput.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Another improvement with HEVC is that the dependencies between the coded data has been changed to further increase throughput.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Context modeling in HEVC has also been improved so that CABAC can better select a context that increases efficiency when compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC specifies 33 directional modes for intra prediction compared with the 8 directional modes for intra prediction specified by H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC also specifies DC intra prediction and planar prediction modes.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The DC intra prediction mode generates a mean value by averaging reference samples and can be used for flat surfaces.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The planar prediction mode in HEVC supports all block sizes defined in HEVC while the planar prediction mode in H.264/MPEG-4 AVC is limited to a block size of 16×16 pixels.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The intra prediction modes use data from neighboring prediction blocks that have been previously decoded from within the same picture.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC has improved precision due to the longer interpolation filter and the elimination of the intermediate rounding error.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] For 4:2:0 video, the chroma samples are interpolated with separable one-dimensional 4-tap filtering to generate eighth-sample precision, while in comparison H.264/MPEG-4 AVC uses only a 2-tap bilinear filter (also with eighth-sample precision).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] As in H.264/MPEG-4 AVC, weighted prediction in HEVC can be used either with uni-prediction (in which a single prediction value is used) or bi-prediction (in which the prediction values from two prediction blocks are combined).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC defines a signed 16-bit range for both horizontal and vertical motion vectors (MVs).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This was added to HEVC at the July 2012 HEVC meeting with the mvLX variables.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC horizontal/vertical MVs have a range of −32768 to 32767 which given the quarter pixel precision used by HEVC allows for a MV range of −8192 to 8191.75 luma samples.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This compares to H.264/MPEG-4 AVC which allows for a horizontal MV range of −2048 to 2047.75 luma samples and a vertical MV range of −512 to 511.75 luma samples.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC allows for two MV modes which are Advanced Motion Vector Prediction (AMVP) and merge mode.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] AMVP uses data from the reference picture and can also use data from adjacent prediction blocks.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The merge mode allows for the MVs to be inherited from neighboring prediction blocks.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Merge mode in HEVC is similar to "skipped" and "direct" motion inference modes in H.264/MPEG-4 AVC but with two improvements.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The first improvement is that HEVC uses index information to select one of several available candidates.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The second improvement is that HEVC uses information from the reference picture list and reference picture index.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC specifies two loop filters that are applied sequentially, with the deblocking filter (DBF) applied first and the sample adaptive offset (SAO) filter applied afterwards.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Both loop filters are applied in the inter-picture prediction loop, i.e. the filtered image is stored in the decoded picture buffer (DPB) as a reference for inter-picture prediction.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The DBF is similar to the one used by H.264/MPEG-4 AVC but with a simpler design and better support for parallel processing.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] In HEVC the DBF only applies to an 8×8 sample grid while with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC the DBF applies to a 4×4 sample grid.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] DBF uses an 8×8 sample grid since it causes no noticeable degradation and significantly improves parallel processing because the DBF no longer causes cascading interactions with other operations.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Another change is that HEVC only allows for three DBF strengths of 0 to 2.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] HEVC also requires that the DBF first apply horizontal filtering for vertical edges to the picture and only after that does it apply vertical filtering for horizontal edges to the picture.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This allows for multiple parallel threads to be used for the DBF.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The SAO filter is applied after the DBF and is designed to allow for better reconstruction of the original signal amplitudes by applying offsets stored in a lookup table in the bitstream.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Per CTB the SAO filter can be disabled or applied in one of two modes: edge offset mode or band offset mode.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The edge offset mode operates by comparing the value of a sample to two of its eight neighbors using one of four directional gradient patterns.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Based on a comparison with these two neighbors, the sample is classified into one of five categories: minimum, maximum, an edge with the sample having the lower value, an edge with the sample having the higher value, or monotonic.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] For each of the first four categories an offset is applied.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The band offset mode applies an offset based on the amplitude of a single sample.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] A sample is categorized by its amplitude into one of 32 bands (histogram bins).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] Offsets are specified for four consecutive of the 32 bands, because in flat areas which are prone to banding artifacts, sample amplitudes tend to be clustered in a small range.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The SAO filter was designed to increase picture quality, reduce banding artifacts, and reduce ringing artifacts.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] The ITU-T version of the standard that added the SCC extensions (approved in December 2016 and published in March 2017) added support for the hybrid log–gamma (HLG) transfer function and the ICtCp color matrix.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p01] This allows the fourth version of HEVC to support both of the HDR transfer functions defined in Rec.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Version 1 of the HEVC standard defines three profiles: **Main**, **Main 10**, and **Main Still Picture**.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Version 2 of HEVC adds 21 range extensions profiles, two scalable extensions profiles, and one multi-view profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC also contains provisions for additional profiles.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Extensions that were added to HEVC include increased bit depth, 4:2:2/4:4:4 chroma sampling, Multiview Video Coding (MVC), and Scalable Video Coding (SVC).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The HEVC range extensions, HEVC scalable extensions, and HEVC multi-view extensions were completed in July 2014.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] In July 2014 a draft of the second version of HEVC was released.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Screen content coding (SCC) extensions were under development for screen content video, which contains text and graphics, with an expected final draft release date of 2015.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A profile is a defined set of coding tools that can be used to create a bitstream that conforms to that profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] An encoder for a profile may choose which coding tools to use as long as it generates a conforming bitstream while a decoder for a profile must support all coding tools that can be used in that profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with 4:2:0 chroma sampling, which is the most common type of video used with consumer devices.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 10 (`Main10`) profile was added at the October 2012 HEVC meeting based on a multicompany proposal JCTVC-K0109 which proposed that a 10-bit profile be added to HEVC for consumer applications.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The proposal said this was to allow for improved video quality and to support the Rec.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] 2020 color space that has become widely used in UHDTV systems and to be able to deliver HDR and color fidelity avoiding the banding artifacts.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A variety of companies supported the proposal which included Ateme, BBC, BSkyB, Cisco, DirecTV, Ericsson, Motorola Mobility, NGCodec, NHK, RAI, ST, SVT, Thomson Video Networks, Technicolor, and ViXS Systems.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 10 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 to 10 bits per sample with 4:2:0 chroma sampling to support consumer use cases.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Main 10 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Main and Main 10.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A higher bit depth allows for a greater number of colors.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] 8 bits per sample allows for 256 shades per primary color (a total of 16.78 million colors) while 10 bits per sample allows for 1024 shades per primary color (a total of 1.07 billion colors).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A higher bit depth allows for a smoother transition of color which resolves the problem known as color banding.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 10 profile allows for improved video quality since it can support video with a higher bit depth than what is supported by the Main profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Additionally, in the Main 10 profile 8-bit video can be coded with a higher bit depth of 10 bits, which allows improved coding efficiency compared to the Main profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Ericsson said the Main 10 profile would bring the benefits of 10 bits per sample video to consumer TV.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] They also said that for higher resolutions there is no bit rate penalty for encoding video at 10 bits per sample.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Imagination Technologies said that 10-bit per sample video would allow for larger color spaces and is required for the Rec.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] 2020 color space that will be used by UHDTV.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] 2020 color space would drive the widespread adoption of 10-bit-per-sample video.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] In a PSNR based performance comparison released in April 2013 the Main 10 profile was compared to the Main profile using a set of 3840×2160 10-bit video sequences.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The 10-bit video sequences were converted to 8 bits for the Main profile and remained at 10 bits for the Main 10 profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The reference PSNR was based on the original 10-bit video sequences.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] In the performance comparison the Main 10 profile provided a 5% bit rate reduction for inter frame video coding compared to the Main profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The performance comparison states that for the tested video sequences the Main 10 profile outperformed the Main profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main Still Picture (`MainStillPicture`) profile allows for a single still picture to be encoded with the same constraints as the Main profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] As a subset of the Main profile the Main Still Picture profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with 4:2:0 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] An objective performance comparison was done in April 2012 in which HEVC reduced the average bit rate for images by 56% compared to JPEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A PSNR based performance comparison for still image compression was done in May 2012 using the HEVC HM 6.0 encoder and the reference software encoders for the other standards.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] For still images HEVC reduced the average bit rate by 15.8% compared to H.264/MPEG-4 AVC, 22.6% compared to JPEG 2000, 30.0% compared to JPEG XR, 31.0% compared to WebP, and 43.0% compared to JPEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A performance comparison for still image compression was done in January 2013 using the HEVC HM 8.0rc2 encoder, Kakadu version 6.0 for JPEG 2000, and IJG version 6b for JPEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The performance comparison used PSNR for the objective assessment and mean opinion score (MOS) values for the subjective assessment.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The subjective assessment used the same test methodology and images as those used by the JPEG committee when it evaluated JPEG XR.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] For 4:2:0 chroma sampled images the average bit rate reduction for HEVC compared to JPEG 2000 was 20.26% for PSNR and 30.96% for MOS while compared to JPEG it was 61.63% for PSNR and 43.10% for MOS.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A PSNR based HEVC performance comparison for still image compression was done in April 2013 by Nokia.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC has a larger performance improvement for higher resolution images than lower resolution images and a larger performance improvement for lower bit rates than higher bit rates.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] For lossy compression to get the same PSNR as HEVC took on average 1.4× more bits with JPEG 2000, 1.6× more bits with JPEG-XR, and 2.3× more bits with JPEG.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A compression efficiency study of HEVC, JPEG, JPEG XR, and WebP was done in October 2013 by Mozilla.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The study showed that HEVC was significantly better at compression than the other image formats that were tested.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Four different methods for comparing image quality were used in the study which were Y-SSIM, RGB-SSIM, IW-SSIM, and PSNR-HVS-M.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] All of the inter frame range extensions profiles have an Intra profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Monochrome profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Monochrome 12 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 12 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Monochrome 16 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 16 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Monochrome 16 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Monochrome 12, and Monochrome 16.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 12 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 12 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0 and 4:2:0 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Main 12 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Monochrome 12, Main, Main 10, and Main 12.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:2:2 10 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 10 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, and 4:2:2 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Main 4:2:2 10 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, Main 10, and Main 4:2:2 10.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:2:2 12 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 12 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, and 4:2:2 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Main 4:2:2 12 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Monochrome 12, Main, Main 10, Main 12, Main 4:2:2 10, and Main 4:2:2 12.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:4:4 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Main 4:4:4 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, and Main 4:4:4.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:4:4 10 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 10 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Main 4:4:4 10 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, Main 10, Main 4:2:2 10, Main 4:4:4, and Main 4:4:4 10.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:4:4 12 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 12 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Main 4:4:4 12 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, Main 10, Main 12, Main 4:2:2 10, Main 4:2:2 12, Main 4:4:4, Main 4:4:4 10, Main 4:4:4 12, and Monochrome 12.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:4:4 16 Intra profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 16 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 16 Intra profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 16 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] 12 times higher than other HEVC profiles, allowing it to have a maximum bit rate 12 times higher than the Main 4:4:4 16 Intra profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 16 Intra profile is designed for high end professional content creation and decoders for this profile are not required to support other profiles.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:4:4 Still Picture profile allows for a single still picture to be encoded with the same constraints as the Main 4:4:4 profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] of the Main 4:4:4 profile, the Main 4:4:4 Still Picture profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main 4:4:4 16 Still Picture profile allows for a single still picture to be encoded with the same constraints as the Main 4:4:4 16 Intra profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] of the Main 4:4:4 16 Intra profile, the Main 4:4:4 16 Still Picture profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 16 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Scalable Main profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Main profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Scalable Main 10 profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Main 10 profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Multiview Main profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Main profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Version 3 of HEVC added one 3D profile: **3D Main**.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The 3D Main profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Main profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended Main profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0 and 4:2:0 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Screen-Extended Main profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, and Screen-Extended Main.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended Main 10 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 10 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0 and 4:2:0 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Screen-Extended Main 10 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, Main 10, Screen-Extended Main, and Screen-Extended Main 10.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended Main 4:4:4 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Screen-Extended Main 4:4:4 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, Main 4:4:4, Screen-Extended Main, and Screen-Extended Main 4:4:4.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended Main 4:4:4 10 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 10 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4 profile has an HbrFactor 6 times higher than most inter frame HEVC profiles allowing it to have a maximum bit rate 6 times higher than the Main 4:4:4 profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: Monochrome, Main, Main 4:4:4, Screen-Extended Main, Screen-Extended Main 4:4:4, Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4, and High Throughput 4:4:4.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4 10 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 10 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4 10 profile has an HbrFactor 6 times higher than most inter frame HEVC profiles allowing it to have a maximum bit rate 6 times higher than the Main 4:4:4 10 profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4 14 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 14 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Screen-Extended High Throughput 4:4:4 14 profile has an HbrFactor 6 times higher than most inter frame HEVC profiles.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 profile has an HbrFactor 6 times higher than most inter frame HEVC profiles allowing it to have a maximum bit rate 6 times higher than the Main 4:4:4 profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the High Throughput 4:4:4 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: High Throughput 4:4:4.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 10 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 10 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 10 profile has an HbrFactor 6 times higher than most inter frame HEVC profiles allowing it to have a maximum bit rate 6 times higher than the Main 4:4:4 10 profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the High Throughput 4:4:4 10 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: High Throughput 4:4:4 and High Throughput 4:4:4 10.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 14 profile allows for a bit depth of 8 bits to 14 bits per sample with support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4 chroma sampling.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The High Throughput 4:4:4 14 profile has an HbrFactor 6 times higher than most inter frame HEVC profiles.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC decoders that conform to the High Throughput 4:4:4 14 profile must be capable of decoding bitstreams made with the following profiles: High Throughput 4:4:4, High Throughput 4:4:4 10, and High Throughput 4:4:4 14.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Scalable Monochrome profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Monochrome profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Scalable Monochrome 12 profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Monochrome 12 profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Scalable Monochrome 16 profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Monochrome 16 profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Scalable Main 4:4:4 profile allows for a base layer that conforms to the Main 4:4:4 profile of HEVC.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The HEVC standard defines two tiers, Main and High, and thirteen levels.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A level is a set of constraints for a bitstream.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] For levels below level 4 only the Main tier is allowed.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main tier is a lower tier than the High tier.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The tiers were made to deal with applications that differ in terms of their maximum bit rate.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The Main tier was designed for most applications while the High tier was designed for very demanding applications.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A decoder that conforms to a given tier/level is required to be capable of decoding all bitstreams that are encoded for that tier/level and for all lower tiers/levels.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The maximum bit rate of the profile is based on the combination of bit depth, chroma sampling, and the type of profile.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] For bit depth the maximum bit rate increases by 1.5× for 12-bit profiles and 2× for 16-bit profiles.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] For chroma sampling the maximum bit rate increases by 1.5× for 4:2:2 profiles and 2× for 4:4:4 profiles.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] For the Intra profiles the maximum bit rate increases by 2×.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The maximum frame rate supported by HEVC is 300 fps.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The MaxDpbSize is the maximum number of pictures in the decoded picture buffer.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Previously decoded pictures are stored in a decoded picture buffer (DPB), and are used by HEVC encoders to form predictions for subsequent pictures.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The maximum number of pictures that can be stored in the DPB, called the DPB capacity, is 6 (including the current picture) for all HEVC levels when operating at the maximum picture size supported by the level.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The DPB capacity (in units of pictures) increases from 6 to 8, 12, or 16 as the picture size decreases from the maximum picture size supported by the level.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The encoder selects which specific pictures are retained in the DPB on a picture-by-picture basis, so the encoder has the flexibility to determine for itself the best way to use the DPB capacity when encoding the video content.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] MPEG has published an amendment which added HEVC support to the MPEG transport stream used by ATSC, DVB, and Blu-ray Disc; MPEG decided not to update the MPEG program stream used by DVD-Video.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] MPEG has also added HEVC support to the ISO base media file format.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC is also supported by the MPEG media transport standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Support for HEVC was added to Matroska starting with the release of MKVToolNix v6.8.0 after a patch from DivX was merged.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] A draft document has been submitted to the Internet Engineering Task Force which describes a method to add HEVC support to the Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Using HEVC's intra frame encoding, a still-image coded format called Better Portable Graphics (BPG) has been proposed by the programmer Fabrice Bellard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] It is essentially a wrapper for images coded using the HEVC Main 4:4:4 16 Still Picture profile with up to 14 bits per sample, although it uses an abbreviated header syntax and adds explicit support for Exif, ICC profiles, and XMP metadata.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] As with its predecessor AVC, software distributors that implement HEVC in products must pay a price per distributed copy.[i] While this licensing model is manageable for paid software, it is an obstacle to most free and open-source software, which is meant to be freely distributable.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] In the opinion of MulticoreWare, the developer of x265, enabling royalty-free software encoders and decoders is in the interest of accelerating HEVC adoption.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] HEVC Advance made an exception that specifically waives the royalties on software-only implementations (both decoders and encoders) when not bundled with hardware.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] However, the exempted software is not free from the licensing obligations of other patent holders (e.g. members of the MPEG LA pool).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Competing formats intended for internet use (VP9 and AV1) are intended to steer clear of these concerns by being royalty free (provided there are no third-party claims of patent rights).
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Since November 2025, Dell and HP announced they will disable HEVC hardware decoding features in UEFI/BIOS level for some entry and middle-end laptops, due to HEVC license fee increases.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] In October 2015, MPEG and VCEG formed Joint Video Exploration Team (JVET) to evaluate available compression technologies and study the requirements for a next-generation video compression standard.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The new algorithm should have 30–50% better compression rate for the same perceptual quality, with support for lossless and subjectively lossless compression.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] Encoding complexity of 10 times that of HEVC is expected.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] JVET issued a final "Call for Proposals" in October 2017, with the first working draft of the Versatile Video Coding (VVC) standard released in April 2018.
[src:heif-format/high-efficiency-video-coding-p02] The VVC standard was finalized on July 6, 2020.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] An **image file format** is a file format for a digital image.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] There are many formats that can be used, such as JPEG, PNG, and GIF.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Most formats up until 2022 were for storing 2D images, not 3D ones.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The data stored in an image file format may be compressed or uncompressed.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] If the data is compressed, it may be done so using lossy compression or lossless compression.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] For graphic design applications, vector formats are often used.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Some image file formats support transparency.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] A 3D image can be represented within a 2D format, as in a stereogram or autostereogram, but this 3D image will not be a true light field, and thereby may cause the vergence–accommodation conflict.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Image files are composed of digital data in one of these formats so that the data can be displayed on a digital (computer) display or printed out using a printer.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] A common method for displaying digital image information has historically been rasterization.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The size of raster image files is positively correlated with the number of pixels in the image and the color depth (bits per pixel).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Images can be compressed in various ways, however.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] A compression algorithm stores either an exact representation or an approximation of the original image in a smaller number of bytes that can be expanded back to its uncompressed form with a corresponding decompression algorithm.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Images with the same number of pixels and color depth can have very different compressed file sizes.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Considering exactly the same compression, number of pixels, and color depth for two images, different graphical complexity of the original images may also result in very different file sizes after compression due to the nature of compression algorithms.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] With some compression formats, images that are less complex may result in smaller compressed file sizes.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] This characteristic sometimes results in a smaller file size for some lossless formats than lossy formats.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] For example, graphically simple images (i.e., images with large continuous regions like line art or animation sequences) may be losslessly compressed into a GIF or PNG format and result in a smaller file size than a lossy JPEG format.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] With vector images, the file size increases only with the addition of more vectors.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] There are two types of image file compression algorithms: lossless and lossy.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression algorithms reduce file size while preserving a perfect copy of the original uncompressed image.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression generally, but not always, results in larger files than lossy compression.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Lossless compression should be used to avoid accumulating stages of re-compression when editing images.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Lossy compression algorithms preserve a representation of the original uncompressed image that may appear to be a perfect copy, but is not a perfect copy.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Often lossy compression is able to achieve smaller file sizes than lossless compression.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Most lossy compression algorithms allow for variable compression that trades image quality for file size.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Including proprietary types, there are hundreds of image file types.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The PNG, JPEG, and GIF formats are most often used to display images on the Internet.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Some of these graphic formats are listed and briefly described below, separated into the two main families of graphics: raster and vector.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Raster images are further divided into formats primarily aimed at (web) delivery (i.e., supporting relatively strong compression) versus formats primarily aimed at authoring or interchange (uncompressed or only relatively weak compression).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] In addition to straight image formats, Metafile formats are portable formats that can include both raster and vector information.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Examples are application-independent formats such as WMF and EMF.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The metafile format is an intermediate format.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Most applications open metafiles and then save them in their own native format.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Page description language refers to formats used to describe the layout of a printed page containing text, objects, and images.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group) is a lossy compression method; JPEG-compressed images are usually stored in the JFIF (JPEG File Interchange Format) or the Exif (Exchangeable Image File Format) file format.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The JPEG filename extension is JPG or JPEG.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Nearly every digital camera can save images in the JPEG format, which supports eight-bit grayscale images and 24-bit color images (eight bits each for red, green, and blue).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] JPEG applies lossy compression to images, which can result in a significant reduction of the file size.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Applications can determine the degree of compression to apply, and the amount of compression affects the visual quality of the result.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] When not too great, the compression does not noticeably affect or detract from the image's quality, but JPEG files suffer generational degradation when repeatedly edited and saved.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The GIF (Graphics Interchange Format) is in normal use limited to an 8-bit palette, or 256 colors (while 24-bit color depth is technically possible).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] GIF is most suitable for storing graphics with few colors, such as simple diagrams, shapes, logos, and cartoon-style images, as it uses LZW lossless compression, which is more effective when large areas have a single color and less effective for photographic or dithered images.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Due to GIF's simplicity and age, it achieved almost universal software support.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Due to its animation capabilities, it is still widely used to provide image animation effects, despite its low compression ratio compared to modern video formats.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The PNG (Portable Network Graphics) file format was created as a free, open-source alternative to GIF.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The PNG file format supports 8-bit (256 colors) paletted images (with optional transparency for all palette colors) and 24-bit truecolor (16 million colors) or 48-bit truecolor with and without an alpha channel – while GIF supports only 8-bit palettes with a single transparent color.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Compared to JPEG, PNG excels when the image has large, uniformly colored areas.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Even for photographs – where JPEG is often the choice for final distribution since its lossy compression typically yields smaller file sizes – PNG is still well-suited to storing images during the editing process because of its lossless compression.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] PNG provides a patent-free replacement for GIF (though GIF is itself now patent-free) and can also replace many common uses of TIFF.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Indexed-color, grayscale, and truecolor images are supported, plus an optional alpha channel.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The Adam7 interlacing allows an early preview, even when only a small percentage of the image data has been transmitted—useful in online viewing applications like web browsers.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] PNG can store gamma and chromaticity data, as well as ICC profiles, for accurate color matching on heterogeneous platforms.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Animated formats derived from PNG are MNG and APNG, which is backwards compatible with PNG and supported by most browsers.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 is a compression standard enabling both lossless and lossy storage.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The compression methods used are different from the ones in standard JFIF/JPEG; they improve quality and compression ratios, but also require more computational power to process.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 also adds features that are missing in JPEG.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It is not nearly as common as JPEG but it is used currently in professional movie editing and distribution (some digital cinemas, for example, use JPEG 2000 for individual movie frames).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] WebP is an open image format released in 2010 that uses both lossless and lossy compression.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It was designed by Google to reduce image file size to speed up web page loading: its principal purpose is to supersede JPEG as the primary format for photographs on the web.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding and uses a container based on RIFF.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] In 2011, Google added an "Extended File Format" allowing WebP support for animation, ICC profile, XMP and Exif metadata, and tiling.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The support for animation allowed for converting older animated GIFs to animated WebP.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The WebP container (i.e., RIFF container for WebP) allows feature support over and above the basic use case of WebP (i.e., a file containing a single image encoded as a VP8 key frame).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Most typical raster formats cannot store HDR data (32 bit floating point values per pixel component), which is why some relatively old or complex formats are still predominant here, and worth mentioning separately.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Newer alternatives are showing up, though.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] RGBE is the format for HDR images originating from Radiance and also supported by Adobe Photoshop.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] JPEG-HDR is a file format from Dolby Labs similar to RGBE encoding, standardized as JPEG XT Part 2.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] JPEG XT Part 7 includes support for encoding floating point HDR images in the base 8-bit JPEG file using enhancement layers encoded with four profiles (A-D); Profile A is based on the RGBE format and Profile B on the XDepth format from Trellis Management.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF) is an image container format that was standardized by MPEG on the basis of the ISO base media file format.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] While HEIF can be used with any image compression format, the HEIF standard specifies the storage of HEVC intra-coded images and HEVC-coded image sequences taking advantage of inter-picture prediction.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] AVIF is an image container, that is used to store AV1 encoded images.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It was created by Alliance for open media (AOMedia) and is completely open source and royalty-free.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It supports encoding images in 8, 10 and 12-bit depth.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] JPEG XL is a royalty-free raster-graphics file format that supports both lossy and lossless compression.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It supports reversible recompression of existing JPEG files, as well as high-precision HDR (up to 32-bit floating point values per pixel component).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It is designed to be usable for both delivery and authoring use cases.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The TIFF (Tag Image File Format) format is a flexible format usually using either the TIFF or TIF filename extension.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The tag structure was designed to be easily extendible, and many vendors have introduced proprietary special-purpose tags – with the result that no one reader handles every flavor of TIFF file.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] TIFFs can be lossy or lossless, depending on the technique chosen for storing the pixel data.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Some offer relatively good lossless compression for bi-level (black&white) images.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Some digital cameras can save images in TIFF format, using the LZW compression algorithm for lossless storage.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] TIFF image format is not widely supported by web browsers, but it remains widely accepted as a photograph file standard in the printing business.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] TIFF can handle device-specific color spaces, such as the CMYK defined by a particular set of printing press inks.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] OCR (Optical Character Recognition) software packages commonly generate some form of TIFF image (often monochromatic) for scanned text pages.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The BMP file format (Windows bitmap) is a raster-based, device-independent file type designed in the early days of computer graphics.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It handles graphic files within the Microsoft Windows OS.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Typically, BMP files are uncompressed and therefore large and lossless; their advantage is their simple structure and wide acceptance in Windows programs.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Netpbm format is a family including the portable pixmap file format (PPM), the portable graymap file format (PGM), and the portable bitmap file format (PBM).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] These are either pure ASCII files or raw binary files with an ASCII header that provide very basic functionality and serve as a lowest common denominator for converting pixmap, graymap, or bitmap files between different platforms.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Several applications refer to them collectively as PNM (Portable Any Map).
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] As opposed to the raster image formats above (where the data describes the characteristics of each individual pixel), vector image formats contain a geometric description which can be rendered smoothly at any desired display size.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] At some point, all vector graphics must be rasterized in order to be displayed on digital monitors.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Vector images may also be displayed with analog CRT technology such as that used in some electronic test equipment, medical monitors, radar displays, laser shows and early video games.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Plotters are printers that use vector data rather than pixel data to draw graphics.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile) is a file format for 2D vector graphics, raster graphics, and text, and is defined by ISO/IEC 8632.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] All graphical elements can be specified in a textual source file that can be compiled into a binary file or one of two text representations.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] CGM provides a means of graphics data interchange for computer representation of 2D graphical information independent from any particular application, system, platform, or device.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It has been adopted to some extent in the areas of technical illustration and professional design, but has largely been superseded by formats such as SVG and DXF.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The Gerber format (aka Extended Gerber, RS-274X) is a 2D bi-level image description format developed by Ucamco.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] It is the de facto standard format for printed circuit board or PCB software.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) is an open standard created and developed by the World Wide Web Consortium to address the need (and attempts of several corporations) for a versatile, scriptable and all-purpose vector format for the web and otherwise.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] The SVG format does not have a compression scheme of its own, but due to the textual nature of XML, an SVG graphic can be compressed using a program such as gzip.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] Because of its scripting potential, SVG is a key component in web applications: interactive web pages that look and act like applications.
[src:heif-format/image-file-format] These are formats containing both pixel and vector data, possible other data, e.g. the interactive features of PDF.
